biconditional-elimination-left¶

Definition¶

biconditional-elimination-left is the inference-rule:

\[\left( P \iff Q \right) \vdash \left( P \implies Q \right)\]

In straightforward language, if P is true if and only if Q is true, it follows that P implies Q.

 2
 3pu.configuration.echo_default = False
 4pu.configuration.echo_inferred_statement = True
 5pu.configuration.echo_axiom_inclusion = True
 6pu.configuration.echo_proof = True
 7
 8# Create a universe-of-discourse with basic objects for the sake of this demonstration.
 9u = pu.UniverseOfDiscourse(echo=True)
10o1 = u.o.declare()
11o2 = u.o.declare()
12o3 = u.o.declare()
13r1 = u.r.declare(2, signal_proposition=True)
14r2 = u.r.declare(1, signal_proposition=True)
15axiom = u.declare_axiom(natural_language='Dummy axiom for demonstration purposes')
16
17# Elaborate a dummy theory with a set of propositions necessary for our demonstration
18t1 = u.t(echo=True)
19theory_axiom = t1.include_axiom(axiom)
20phi1 = t1.i.axiom_interpretation.infer_statement(theory_axiom,
21    (r1(o1, o2) | u.r.biconditional | r2(o3)))
22
23# And finally, use the biconditional-introduction inference-rule:
24pu.configuration.echo_proof = True
25proposition_of_interest = t1.i.biconditional_elimination_left.infer_statement(p_iff_q=phi1,
26    subtitle='The proposition of interest', echo=True)
27
28print(proposition_of_interest.rep_report())
29pass

Plaintext output

texttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttexttext
Let "U2" be a universe-of-discourse.

Let "T1" be a theory-elaboration-sequence in U2.

Axiom (T1.A1): Let axiom A1 "Dummy axiom for demonstration purposes" be included (postulated) in T1.

Proposition (T1.P1): (r1(o1, o2) <==> r2(o3)). Proof: "Dummy axiom for demonstration purposes" is postulated by axiom (A1). (r1(o1, o2) <==> r2(o3)) is a valid formula statement interpreted from that axiom.Therefore, by the axiom-interpretation inference rule: A |- P, it follows that (r1(o1, o2) <==> r2(o3)). QED

Warning (warning1): By design, punctilious assures the syntactical correctness of package, but does not perform any semantic verification. Therefore, the usage of inference-rules that interpret content (i.e. axiom-interpretation and definition-interpretation) is critically dependent on the correctness of the content translation performed by the theory author, from axiom or definition natural language, to formulae.

Proposition (T1.P2) - The proposition of interest: (r1(o1, o2) ==> r2(o3)). Proof: (r1(o1, o2) <==> r2(o3)), of the form (P1 <==> Q1), follows from prop. (P1). Therefore, by the biconditional-elimination-left inference rule: ((P1 <==> Q1) |- (P1 ==> Q1)), it follows that (r1(o1, o2) ==> r2(o3)). QED

Proposition (T1.P2) - The proposition of interest: (r1(o1, o2) ==> r2(o3)). Proof: (r1(o1, o2) <==> r2(o3)), of the form (P1 <==> Q1), follows from prop. (P1). Therefore, by the biconditional-elimination-left inference rule: ((P1 <==> Q1) |- (P1 ==> Q1)), it follows that (r1(o1, o2) ==> r2(o3)). QED
